# .gitleaksignore — allowlist for gitleaks false-positive fingerprints.
#
# All entries below are from ioguard's own test fixtures and detector-pattern
# code — not real credentials. ioguard is a secret-detection tool: it must
# contain examples of the patterns it detects, which naturally triggers the
# same rules it implements.
#
# Groups:
#   A. crates/ioguard-core/src/detectors/secret.rs
#      — unit-test vectors and PEM/key pattern literals embedded in the
#        detector implementation. Most literals are already split via .concat()
#        to avoid false-positives in most scanners; a subset remains detectable.
#
#   B. corpus/must-block/
#      — synthetic test fixtures used for integration / acceptance testing.
#        Each file holds exactly one credential-shaped string so the test suite
#        can assert ioguard blocks it.
#
#   C. rules/secret.toml
#      — gitleaks-compatible rule definitions that include example / description
#        strings matching the rules they define.
#
#   D. .workhorse/phases/
#      — AI-generated work notes (planning artefacts) that quoted example
#        credential strings during initial project scaffolding. These files are
#        not shipped; they are in-repo documentation only.
#
# Note: the CI secret-scan job runs on push/PR only
# (if: github.event_name != 'schedule'). The weekly scheduled run
# intentionally skips secret scanning — it only runs cargo-deny advisories.
# This asymmetry is by design, not config drift.

